```python
class Pipeline:
    def __init__(self, steps): self.steps=steps   # [(transformer...), estimator]
    def fit(self, X, y):
        for t in self.steps[:-1]: X=t.fit(X).transform(X)
        self.steps[-1].fit(X, y); return self
    def predict(self, X):
        for t in self.steps[:-1]: X=t.transform(X)
        return self.steps[-1].predict(X)
```

A pipeline packages preprocessing + model into one fitted object. Versus scattered notebook cells, it's **reproducible** (same steps, same order, every time), **serializable** (ship the whole thing), and — critically — it makes leakage hard, because transforms are `fit` on training data only and merely `transform` at predict time.
